olume Comparison |\n| A volume comparison of residential and commercial consumption calculated with two methodologies. |\n\nNatural Gas Monthly Contacts\n\n## Highlights\n\n﻿\n\n#### May Natural Gas Monthly, containing data for March 2026\n\n- Gross withdrawals: 4,201 Bcf for the month, or 135.5 Bcf/d\n- Highest daily rate for the month of March since 1980, the earliest year in this dataset\n\n- Estimated natural gas consumption in March 2026 was 2,779 Bcf, or 89.6 Bcf/d\n- A 1.0% increase compared with March 2025 (88.7 Bcf/d)\n\n- Residential deliveries: 481 Bcf for the month, or 15.5 Bcf/d\n- An 8.7% decrease compared with March 2025 (17.0 Bcf/d)\n- Lowest rate of natural gas residential deliveries for the month of March since 2016\n\n- Commercial deliveries: 349 Bcf for the month, or 11.3 Bcf/d\n- A 4.4% decrease compared with March 2025 (11.8 Bcf/d)\n\n- Industrial deliveries: 741 Bcf for the month, or 23.9 Bcf/d\n- A 0.5% decrease compared with March 2025 (24.0 Bcf/d)\n- Lowest rate of natural gas industrial deliveries for the month of March since 2021\n\n- Electric power deliveries: 918 Bcf for the month, or 29.6 Bcf/d\n- A 10.6% increase compared with March 2025 (26.8 Bcf/d)\n\n- Total natural gas imports: 239 Bcf for the month, or 7.7 Bcf/d\n- A 9.1% decrease compared with March 2025 (8.5 Bcf/d)\n- Lowest daily rate of natural gas imports for the month of March since 2021\n\n- Total natural gas exports: 891 Bcf for the month, or 28.7 Bcf/d\n- An 18.3% increase compared with March 2025 (24.3 Bcf/d)\n- Highest daily rate of natural gas exports for any month since we began tracking them in 1973\n- Liquefied natural gas (LNG) exports: The daily rate of LNG exports in March 2026 was 25.1% higher than the daily rate in March 2025, the highest rate for any month since we began tracking LNG exports in 1997. In March 2026, the United States exported 18.5 Bcf/d of LNG to 34 countries.\n\n## Related\n\n- Natural Gas survey forms\n- Weekly Natural Gas Storage Report\n- 